\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=\boxed{D^{-1}C^{-1}B^{-1}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sum of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=A^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, or equivalently the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=\boxed{\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We want to compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=A^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)=D^{-1}\underbrace{C^{-1}\underbrace{B^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)}_{c}}_{d}.
\]

\end_inset

As usual, we want to do this without explicitly multiplying or inverting
 matrices, since that is a lot more effort than we usually need.
 In particular, we can break it into the following steps.
 (You can get a lot of partial credit here just by outlining the steps below:
 backsubstitution, elimination, diagonal solve.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(Note that explicitly multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $A=BCD$
\end_inset

 and then solving 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=[1,1,1,1]$
\end_inset

 by elimination is also possible, but is substantially more work.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $BC$
\end_inset

 is more work than handling 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 separately via backsubstitution, and multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $CD$
\end_inset

 is also more work than solving 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 separately.
 Think of the arithmetic counts: backsubstitution takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim n^{2}$
\end_inset

 operations, while multiplying two matrices is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim n^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, computing 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}d$
\end_inset

 requires only 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 divisions for a diagonal 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, whereas multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 by a diagonal matrix takes 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 multiplications.
 If the matrix is already factored for you into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrices, you waste a lot of effort if you throw that factorization away
 by multiplying the factors together!)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $c=B^{-1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

is upper-triangular, we can do this by back-substitution, from bottom to
 top: 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{4}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{3}=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=1-3c_{4}=-2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=1-2c_{3}=3$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\left(\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2\\
-1\\
1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $d=C^{-1}c$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Cd=c$
\end_inset

.
 We proceed by elimination, augmenting 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 with the right-hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\underbrace{\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 2 & -1 & 0\\
1 & 4 & 0 & 1
\end{array}}_{C}\underbrace{\mathbf{\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2\\
-1\\
1
\end{array}}}_{c}\right) & \rightsquigarrow\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 2 & -1 & 0\\
0 & 4 & -2 & 1
\end{array}\mathbf{\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2\\
-1\\
-2
\end{array}}\right)\rightsquigarrow\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & -1\\
0 & 0 & -2 & -1
\end{array}\mathbf{\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2\\
1\\
2
\end{array}}\right),\\
 & \rightsquigarrow\left(\underbrace{\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & 2 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 0 & 1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & -1\\
0 & 0 &  & 1
\end{array}}_{U}\mathbf{\begin{array}{c}
3\\
-2\\
1\\
0
\end{array}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which we then solve by backsubstitution (bottom to top), to get 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{4}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{3}=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=(-2-d_{4})/2=-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}=3-2d_{3}=5$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d=\left(\begin{array}{c}
5\\
-1\\
-1\\
0
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, compute 
\begin_inset Formula $x=D^{-1}d$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix, this is easy: we just divide 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 by the diagonal elements, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\boxed{\left(\begin{array}{c}
5/2\\
-1\\
1/2\\
0
\end{array}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
